Parliament did not ratify Tymosenko's release amendment
The Ukrainian parliament has refused, as part of an amendment to the criminal law, the plan to cancel the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the opposition leader.
The deputies refused at second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing the penalties for economic offenses, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having reached a seemingly disadvantageous deal with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must rule on the convicted woman's appeal in December.
Tymosenko calls the ruling a political revenge of the regime and has caused a process of suspicions of court bias also in the west.
The plan to annul paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
