The diet of an obese child: does not take breakfast and takes cold meats for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren are above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, for example, cold cuts are found 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of small fat people sport is also not a habit, which is now the case of most schoolchildren today - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents find time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of children who are overweight or obese is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough physical exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed indicate, for example, eating breakfast five times a day – in case – lunch – snack – dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet,” says one of the results of the survey.
Without breakfast and cold meats for dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes a few basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of student families eat at the same time.
In most families, each has their own breakfast.
And the worst that has been noted is that a tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in the families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed more often.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned do sports regularly but for parents this is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food based on their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sweets.
“The most alarming is in particular a great preference for sweetened lemonades,” said the survey results.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place just in front of the white meat.
Children did not want starchy foods at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Focus on health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a control of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness session "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was a strong desire to move towards a healthy diet," say the results of the survey.
The most striking was, for example, when it came to sweetened lemonades as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often ticked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would cut down on sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech speciality of bread flour or potato dumplings).
