History of IBM: From cheese slices to flights into the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York City a hundred years ago; it originally had the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a trademark used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 chaired the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the firm’s founder – it was Watson’s ideas that have so far underpinned the company’s identity and culture.
Watson ran the firm until 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce – from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
During Watson's first four years of leadership, revenue increased to $9 million and the firm began to expand to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight to the Moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 came onto the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to take care of consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM for the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
IBM recently developed a “Smarter Commerce” platform that helps salespeople manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in our territory as well.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that deals with speech recognition.
