How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mostly to socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A big exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually for example to Poland or the Soviet Union he needed a letter of invitation otherwise the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West however it was necessary to wait in line all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs spent most of their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989, the Czechs have experienced a great revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million vacation days in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in neighbouring countries of the west has caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by air to the west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations put Czechs to sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a trip by Czechs at that time was to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades to be able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage increased which caused around 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel travel agencies have started since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter connections that through contracts have greatly reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 90s of the last century the Czechs had visa-free connections with practically most of the developed countries of the world apart from the US which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to far away hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to completely fall into the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 kroner per person for holidays abroad including ancillary charges. kroner per person.
