21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion That Moved
D'Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions of Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and acts as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, glass sheds, bright and bold looks and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of Austrian architect Karl schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its light and suspended steel and glass construction.
The construction is considered until today as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian World's Fair.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the World's Fair in the Swiss Garden at Vienna's South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang works of art, so not a good environment.
However it was used for as long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "House of the 21st century" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck from any point of view.
The new beginning was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she particularly carried out the transformation work with politicians and the protection of monuments, she obtained public funds and private sponsoring and established it.
With the exception of contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookshop are there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded Joseph Olbracht's secession and won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "virtually every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness following its move to Vienna and by its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a sinkhole in energy," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulated glass reinforced with glass fibers was laid and the roof replaced by a special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new farm, a dimmed light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - this is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remained, the house is painted in a rust protection shade of red-brown color.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as it once was.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for the monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive had to be found, and that also please the protection office monuments," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to raw ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the Pavilion, “which came from Brussels,” Krischanitz said recently, a typical “Drop-in-the-City” story.
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a stroke of luck of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands the newly planned "neighborhood of the central station", with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may happen: the 21st century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city in order to get a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
