Peter Englund’s new book, “The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War,” begins with a long list of characters that are heart-wrenching.
One tip to get started: carefully tear this page apart and make it your bookmark.
In this romantic tale by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
Here he wrote an extraordinary book which he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history."
It has a few well-known names, important treaties, or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and materials.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it could look like" and includes "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and salespeople.
Some will become heroes.
Others are prisoners of war, some will lose limbs, some will go mad, some will lose their lives.
Their lives are flickering here like the candles of a church: while some are dying out, new ones are being rekindled.
Peter Englund's book deviates from traditional history books.
He refutes the idea that the First World War can only be summed up by the terrible trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When cannon shots sound in the distance, and you are a stay-at-home mom, are you staying or running away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been fleshed out by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
"Beauty and Grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German deep-sea fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other previously published documents.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved through the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most deal with deprivation and the ability to cope.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, faux aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It continues on replacement food in Germany.
He describes "meat made of cooked rice crushed into sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
He claims that "837 licensed substitute meats are registered in sausage production. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
