Walls have eyes: Researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy sharing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having been caught in a murderous madness in Norway in July leaving 77 victims, was faced with his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time prior to the attack on his computer, chatting with a few of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networking sites.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Log in to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to find them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific accuracy – the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. They targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to take a survey. The questions asked were about their level of education, attitudes toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
By getting in touch with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens.”
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new go-to tool in the hands of scientists.
Focus groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, through "Likes", wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, the “data supernova” is generating a research explosion, increasing the number of research jobs whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you could not approach on the street.
“Before, when you were trying to investigate people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You had to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you in,” says Jamie Bartlett.
“Facebook avoids all of this – you have direct access to their information.”
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who talked on Facebook about their drunken exploits were enormously more likely to be alcoholics than discreet students about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that students’ colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would speak too often about alcohol.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, says the Washington Post.
“We know how to identify children who are at risk, and who would not otherwise be recognized.”
Facebook also constantly accesses its users’ information.
The site’s data-driven team studied statistics regarding the love situation and Valentine’s Day, turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (thanks to the information only available – champions of digital freedom have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to other people for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information other than through the Internet, there is something else entirely online.
“I don’t think many users have ever thought about a researcher being able to study their profile,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the Knowledge Lab in London, according to a 2006 study he conducted while observing his students’ Facebook walls.
"As far as they knew, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user’s wall.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two completely different things,” Selwyn said.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notebook and a pen are the best tools you can use.
“Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people,” he says.
“Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect – and the social is not in front of a computer.”
