7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview at the Cinema This Week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford – distinguished by technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans may find most telling in a Steve Jobs interview recently found and which will be released this week in the first part of a film in the main markets, is how much this creative spirit had understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a flowchart enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease that makes them think that a great idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a great idea from a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sat down for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it had been about 10 years since Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies disappeared in the transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a complete video was found in the director's garage.
This video, slightly edited, is the basis of the 68-minute film entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be screened in cinemas next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly excited to expose tech philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, giving him elbows to make him accelerate and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, we find a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision on the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then implements them immediately.
Here is a quick recap of seven remarkable sequences from Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
“In all these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to detail his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" assessed on a nose-eye view, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a trick at the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack telephone networks and make long-distance calls for free.
The device has been the subject of much prior writing, but Steve Jobs’ euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We would wrap the ball around different things half a dozen times and you’d scream into the public phone and it would happen to you a minute later on the public phone next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and through this Blue Box we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn't know much about each other, but we invented a little thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to tell a wonderful story that he and Wozniak developed: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go off in laughter just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett's canvassing):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he looks for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP’s employees to visit the company’s research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first desktop computer ever designed.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode ray tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the Improvisation of Innovation:
Several times in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a whim.
Early in his career, as he settled down to sell a few circuit boards, a client asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 days of credit, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big fights... they yelled at me pretending it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that turned out to be incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are running out of steam:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industrial leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then what?”
You have a monopoly of the market, so the company is not more successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [it’s those types of people] who end up leading companies and product staff are being sidelined from decision making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can’t imagine designing a good product versus a bad product – the manual labor required.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire IT industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They won defeat to victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
“A huge amount of manual work separates a great idea from a great product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by putting them together.
Finally, decisions are made out of personal taste. It’s about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you’re creating.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
That's part of what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
