During the first year of management of Mario Lopez Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has decreased and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdez, self-called of the change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing losses of trillions for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the Jelly Allocation Report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582 million 835 hectares have been damaged, of which 78.03 percent have suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent have suffered partial damage, the main crops affected have been vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the rate of unemployment of the State during the first three trimesters of the year has been observed an accelerated increase, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 sinaloens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Active Economic Population 9 in the second trimester the rate has become
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to the economist Gerardo Lopez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars in an illicit way it’s not easy that they work to earn them, that they invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Migration Detained
Lepez Cervantes pointed out that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been limited, first because of the difficulties of entry and second because by entering they already have a lot of difficulty to find work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market worsens by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that prevails between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the state’s lag is low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Work and Social Forecasting.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, far below the national average, which stands at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Economy Secretariat from January to June the State FDI reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the State Government records a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government requested in July at the public congress the approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the objective of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November the economy has seen no profit in the economy.
Reactions
For the representatives of the employer sector, the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdés demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, president of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the State Government.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year has been really poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have to align the effort of all and especially the good already synchronized progress of this new government team, let's hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo Lopez said events like the frosts at the beginning of the year held back the state’s economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, between which the frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not run fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations that we had," he says.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronate Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that one wants to channel the State towards productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we think it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and the economic direction of the state, because it is important that we devastate the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
“In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term programma,” he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
