Court approves 'analogue cut' in Mexico in 2015
The substitution of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been met.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderon did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be followed to make the transition to digital terrestrial television a reality.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation of radio and television is an attribution reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favor of the project have voted only Zaldavar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and even Sanchez Cordero.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions provided for by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the ministers also resolved to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sanchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the minister president said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also do not consider that if he did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is the direction of the State.
The substitution of digital signals for analog signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and is reflected in better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization that involves a decision of public interest that has not only a technical dimension, “because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues.”
These issues, he stressed, “require the operation of an entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompassing a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State”.
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, has somehow invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, for it ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws issued by the Legislature, he assured.
The possibility of a "vote-by-vote" countdown is analysed in Michoacan
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between the first and second place of the governor election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacin, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP) the difference between the first and second place of the election of the governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this sense, the president of the General Council of the Michoacàn Electoral Institute (IEM), Maria de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, the past 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with the federal reform in electoral matters.
It will be recalled that Michoacon did not ratify either his Political Constitution or his State Electoral Code or his Electoral Justice Law, at the same time that the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal period for this electoral process to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the deadlines provided by the Law of the Official State Journal, with a few objections.
On the same November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the representative of the state for constitutional reforms, because it has no right to "sanction or contest them".
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote", Maria de los Angeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out the partial and total counts of the votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there are no minutes of voting and counting in the file of the ballot box is not found in the president of the latter; or there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total number of votes received in all the ballot boxes of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate supposed to be the winner of the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the ballot is equal or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the party and/or coalition that presented the second of the reported candidates.
The total number of votes may also be counted if, at the end of the joint tally, it appears that the difference between the candidate who is supposed to be the winner and that of the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party from which the candidate came second, in which case the electoral packages that were the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
