During the press conference, TBS licensee Pérez J?come listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical standards, the flight was conducted according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM referred to adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced to the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were layers of cloudiness at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions the crew searched for a lower height area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
The location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remnants in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral path.
The aircraft's residual dispersion model suggests that the helicopter collided with the ground under structural integrity conditions.
Traces of fire or explosion were not detected:
At the scene of the accident there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of any type of explosion or fire.
