MSS Announces Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people, called protocol 'Génétique de l'obesité des enfants et adolescents' which will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Investigation and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
To the investigation is invited to participate the population entitled or not, to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the proofs are made to the minors every Saturday from 8:00 hours.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Sports Unit Cuauhtémoc (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualc?ylt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the target of 500 or 600 miners, the study will continue in the Sports Unit Independencia (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sports Unit Morelos (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that to know the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and youth risk factors to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of the specific questionnaires relating to diet.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that Saturdays will be applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, height, circumference of the waist), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (the aim is to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lopez pointed out that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 reported that in only six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity and in the case of girls of 47 percent; in the case of overweight there was also a dramatic increase," stressed the specialist of the IMSS.
He said the rationale for searching for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others by its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American heredity, a 30 percent European and a five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity results in the inability to burn the excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the full assessment of the children, which makes it possible to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and doctors give it in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Another cause is high caloric intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pâté with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better efficiency, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the indications that the pavement was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand blackcurrants each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera N?jera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the asphalt pavement is adequate, the blackcurrants could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Najera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that on the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in their majority were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he reported, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating effort, it allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, it would spread better, opined the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called the rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
Being the part of the paver that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be neat.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that spoils is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be cured at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrants and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrants.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it possible to repair blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
