So was the work of Cali's person who identified Alfonso Cano's corpse
A typist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
In the past 4 November a typewriter of the CTI of Cali has made history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", by confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the CTI’s local offices, this week it was the “availability” trick of Eliazar Gonzalez, a Puerto Tejada man who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, Gonzalez worked in the municipalities of Choco, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the corpses were to be identified.
The year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking adequate courses, he specialized in typing, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is to say the palms and the feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that it was suspected that one of them was that of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo Leon S?enz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a local farmer, without glasses and much leaner.
But the fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a sampler and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzan that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In Search of the Footprint
For a typist from Sijon de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar Gonzalez, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can be crucial in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured individuals.
When captured, many offenders present false ID cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher told that in one case of theft he had to remove a part of the wall of a house, because in this place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
“The walls are difficult because they are not adequate areas to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different thefts,” he recalls.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently a dead man was found, with bottles of drink around him.
Through investigation it was determined that a relative may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it does not guarantee that he is the murderer, it puts him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI typist explained that "fingerprints of objects are extracted with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a sampler or strip is used to collect them.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the database of declines, or to the National Civil Registry.
“The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians,” the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is how one shows in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything you touch does not necessarily become an imprint.
It can be used, however, if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
The "indignant" challenge the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters jostled in front of Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part of the people acceded to the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement defied New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter, thanks to a court order, instead of Manhattan, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another park of the Big Apple.
Hundreds of protesters were scrambling in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a judicial order that allows the "undigned" to camp again in this place, while the other part of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
“Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will move to another place and continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful protests,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray detailed that the response of the “outraged” to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order that prohibited the forced evacuation of the place and allowed the protesters to stay in the camp.
In addition, the 'undigned' occupied a new park at the confluence of the Canal Street and Sixth Avenue power plants, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church Parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some protesters, even though Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization claims that there are hundreds of people who have settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders has moved in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene on their behalf before the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a private property enclosure - remains closed pending the holding of a judicial hearing scheduled for Tuesday during which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analysed.
A few displaced protesters were carrying and distributing copies of the court order at that time and even handing it over to officers who were monitoring the square, which caused “some small clashes,” said Bray, who denounced the fact that some officials beat the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evacuating members of Occupy Wall Street or enforcing “laws published after the occupation began or prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they previously used.”
Mayor Bloomberg told reporters that because of the court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, but warned that local laws do not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councilor personally defended the early morning evacuation at Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the protesters were “violating the law”.
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the square because it became “a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases, to harm other people,” because “some stores had received threats” and residents were afraid “for their quality of life.”
“This morning’s early morning evacuation was repulsive and demonstrates that basically Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of American workers,” added the spokesman of the movement, who accused the mayor of “not respecting freedom of expression.”
“Occupy Wall Street” officials also said they do not plan to hold “big actions” for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on Sept. 17.
