Japan Reborn After Earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, recovering from the devastating earthquake that became the nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in Japan since the Second World War.
Initial estimates by the Tokyo government have calculated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, gross domestic product data between July and September were used to definitively turn the page: GDP rose 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rates.
That recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - assumes, in addition, the largest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is due, in part, to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital spending observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan’s GDP.
This variable rose 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "safe haven values" elected by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the troubled U.S. forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of major technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, made responsible for their weak results between July and September the contribution of the yen.
While markets continue to be headquartered in peripheral EU countries, Yoshihiko Noda’s government does not let down its guard.
“We need to keep track of the risks that remain, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand’s floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Motohisa Furukawa, secretary of state for economic policy.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging at all.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) reported that the majority of member countries presented clearer signals of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are held back.
As it dropped four decimals to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below average, which is in the 100 level, n dropping eight decimals to 99.13 points.
