What is sick leave fraud?
After the allocations, the UMP and the government launched the offensive on sick leave.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be Tuesday, November 15 in Bordeaux to visit a family allowance fund, and deliver a speech on the theme - recurrent since 2007 - of the fight against social fraud and the assistantship.
And to accompany this offensive, which starts from a desire to save money in a context of rigor, but is no less indicative of an axis of the presidential campaign on the right, the majority wants to focus on sick leave.
First, for the purpose of budget savings: the government plans to impose on private employees a fourth day of deficiency before taking charge of a stoppage of work.
In other words, without a specific company agreement, an employee who becomes ill would lose four days’ salary, thus at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that risks generating anger, but that would bring 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, more symbolic in scope: to impose on civil servants a day of absence without compensation in the event of a stoppage of work (they have so far no waiting period, against three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority is also relaunching the topic of fraud, this time targeting abuses related to work stoppages.
"The controls are going to be much more important and, in addition, if you are taken, you will reimburse," warned Xavier Bertrand on RTL's microphone, Sunday, November 13.
As with other cases, the advertising effects appear to be somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
Since 2002, it has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives, which have most often borne fruit.
The French are no more sick than anywhere else in Europe.
Let us first look at the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than 237 million euros of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, in 2008 daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure, with 11.3 billion euros.
Of this amount, 46% were for maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% were for sick leave, i.e. 6.2 billion euros.
That’s 2.5% of health care spending.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that hides certain gaps: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management site Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees interviewed said they had not taken any sick days.
Another study, this time from Health Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to a month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more prone to work stoppages than elsewhere.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (whether for health reasons or not) varied between 10% and 11% in France, compared to 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Sick leave fraud represents very little in the face of black work.
As for fraud, it only reaches a small scale.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 has led to systematic checks on sick leave of more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million checks, the CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 carried out for short-term stops were "unjustified or too long", or 37,050 cases.
In the case of arrests of more than 45 days, systematically monitored, there were 11% of "inadapted or unjustified" cases out of 1.2 million, or 132,000.
In total, therefore 169 000 "unjustified" cases, out of several million employees who have had a sick leave.
A figure that represents very little compared, for example, to that of work in the dark.
According to MP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would represent 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud to the latter.
