Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says expert committee
Canadians live in denial of death, says Royal Society of Canada report
When it comes to palliative care, the committee is calling for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk with their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of a major report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
From the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that “the medicalization of death in Canada has spawned a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death.”
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, report the experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
Despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Overall, the rate is highest in Quebec, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on non-competent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signer of the report, said yesterday in a teleconference that more cases of these excesses would be found precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
“Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,” Downie said.
Canadians Support Euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favor of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering, according to a survey Angus Reid conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled are less valuable.
For those who have been involved in assisted suicide, 41% said they should not be prosecuted.
In terms of maintaining or discontinuing care with a patient, the situation is less clear, say the authors of the report.
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be indicated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Expert Panel also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect a refusal of care at the end of life, without fear of criminal prosecution.
When it comes to palliative care, the committee is calling for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee asks that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
