Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the position of the experts who signed the report as "extreme", among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and is over 18 could ask for help to commit suicide," said Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report.
Mr. Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
“In society,” he says, “there are markers and constraints.”
Health law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed “strong opposition” to the report’s findings, which she called a “pro-euthanasia protest.”
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, specifically challenges the report’s data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, namely the Netherlands and Oregon.
