A “Golden Rule” in the Constitution
Austria's ruling Social Democratic/Christian Democrat grand coalition government on Tuesday decided to include a budget "golden rule" in the constitution to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible deterioration by the rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the end of a Council of Ministers, while Austria's public debt is 74.6%, well above the criterion of 60% maximum set by the Maastricht Treaty, but significantly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were lowered by just one notch, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an extra three billion euros in interest every year,” said Michael Spindelegger, vice-chancellor and Christian Democrat foreign minister.
Austria is following up on a request from the summit in Brussels of the euro zone member countries on 26 October: the heads of state and government had then called for the inclusion by the end of 2012 of the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or in a law of the same value.
The system adopted by the Austrian government is closer to the "German model", as Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural public deficit will have to decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, as of 2017, the federal government’s structural public deficit will not have to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The aim is to raise public debt to 60% by 2020/21, as set out in the Maastricht Treaty.
