Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If there is one subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is indeed energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is healthy that an election meeting is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place that nuclear power holds.
The debate will be fruitful only if it explores the full economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to overcome the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity permanently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight against climate disruption, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just intends to build only the latest generation of power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its fleet by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the accident at Three Mile Island.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality thwarts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, a jump in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is worth pondering.
European champion of wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas because of the intermittent wind; under which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Therefore, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful declarations on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show a principled opposition to this energy, the polls show.
Recall that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it trains a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and makes them very creator of non-relocatable jobs.
If France were to decide to get out of nuclear power, it would be sacrificing many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros a year of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity generation, any more than there is a diabolical one.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a safety authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants as well as on the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession of safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident resulted from two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
The result of this approach and cooperation between the French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians wishing to build a power plant, the stop of its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by giving them the freeway to seize the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - overcrowding of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has been the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming in passing that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic perspective.
There is a fairly broad consensus on this issue between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on both left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that we will deign to give to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be paying electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anaemia growth and harms employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they risk replacing domestic workers, especially the low-skilled, who are putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, working for the most part in job-scarce sectors.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not match the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that immigrant arrivals have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages in the long term.
This does not take into account the fact that the diversity provided by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to public budgets on average over his entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to look for the missing growth points “with teeth”.
The teeth in question, by serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought
Democracy is a precious good; it is also a fragile good.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, knew throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have thought that it would be enough, for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct manner possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first and foremost a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinodia of the true-false Greek referendum will have had in this respect the value of two revelations: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic combat have now shifted, and that, for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to the needs and in a dispersed order.
A white-sign to the absolute European monarch or a leap with feet joined in the void of nationalist withdrawal: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want to cutlets but a common, full-fledged, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - there is no longer any way to stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that bows to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
There are concerns about sovereignty transfers to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the steering of the European project.
Because it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without complete democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After having long fought against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic government.
All right.
But to think of it without a stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must assume a new stage of European construction.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The revolution in interests was not enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more politically democratic Europe, a genuine European popular sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
