The Terrorist Axis
The analysis of past calls points to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who has spent a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram and the other to a man who claims to be close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we must probably wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between AQIM and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months these “supports” had been increasingly evident in Boko Haram’s evolution and discourses, or in its modus operandi, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices that are increasingly complex and of the same quality as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore pressured Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of illuminants unworthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means in Hausa "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes itself and demands strict respect for sharia while its militants engage in the fight against the impious central government.
The latter are aimed first of all at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active, multiplying attacks against police stations.
The reaction of Abuja is, as usual, without nuances.
The army invades the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
From then on, the sect would become radicalized and leave its northern strongholds.
Last Christmas, she claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it was again in Abuja that Boko Haram attacked the secure headquarters of the police during a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia via Nigeria now worries all security specialists.
While Aqmi has taken over Mali and Niger, as Somalis from al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat in the heart of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready "to share all the intelligence".
The World According to Republican Presidential Candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete for simplicity and ignorance.
Can an America weakened by the crisis manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
Over the past few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have been ramping up their thunderous foreign policy statements and shortcuts, traditionally a Republican hot spot.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, slogans – often unsupported – are flying.
Mitt Romney, who is best placed in the race to appoint the “Great Old Party,” has threatened to drag the Chinese to the WTO and implicate them “for manipulating their currency,” a promising theme in an America exasperated by the migration of swathes of its industry to Asia.
So much the worse if it involves the outbreak of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate to have a sophisticated foreign policy vision, nearly strangled himself in the face of an attitude that “flattering” emotions.
He called for a muscular but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who stagnates in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
In the image of Reagan
Romney also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
“If I am elected, I will stop Iran,” he boasted.
“If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb.”
He also vowed to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to meet his obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-placed candidate, displays an embarrassing lack of knowledge of the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing is “trying to develop a nuclear capability” – seemingly unaware of the fact that China has held the military atom since 1964!
Texas Gov. Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes against Iran, says he is ready to engage the U.S. military in Mexico against the drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
We are far from the Republican candidate of 2008, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current president reply that Reagan too had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine when it came to anti-terrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the too hasty departure of the "boys" from Iraq, on his procrastinations in Libya, thus labeling him as weak.
But the attack is not so easy.
The public is rather positive about Obama’s national security record, which eliminated bin Laden.
From Iraq, it is wary of military interventions that lead to stagnation.
And, arguing that America needs to be economically rebuilt to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more justly.
Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia by passing through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that directly connects, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned the wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe via a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same course.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site looks like a victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland, in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained a greater security of its supplies.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily consuming gas and whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon when inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how the major gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by Gazprom executives, present in large numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of steel sheathed with concrete in order to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens M?ller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which nothing interrupts along its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but project officials gave it up while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company permanently establish itself off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Muller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it delivers accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo any repairs.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains 51% of the shares.
Joining them were Germany’s E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Netherlands’ Gasunie and France’s GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transmission capacity to the company for 20 renewable years.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Muller.
30% of the financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to recoup their costs, since only Gazprom bears the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a off-white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took care of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has brought back to life an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
It is far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw up a robot portrait of the buyer, because the notebook appeals to the businessman, the student and the professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now has almost 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
“We followed the times and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” says Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers ... The brand is available on a whole range of supports.
In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Discouraging?
“No,” says Eric Blanchet, executive director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
"The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable."
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.”
“However, there is still a lot to do.”
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before accessing employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to an average of 38%.
In short, these are all criteria that make it particularly difficult to return to work, and that "constitute the crux of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
Here are the objective brakes.
There remains the unsaid, the mentalities that evolve, certainly, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities ".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The latest figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
