Portugal is very confident
Paulo Bento’s Portugal starts with a lot of optimism its return playoff against Bosnia (22:00), this Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the end, both teams lacked realism.
“At the end of these 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country.”
Paulo Bento is already there, in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is no shadow of a doubt, the Selecçao, which he has been in control of since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Portugal is only 90 minutes away from happiness.
But there is a game to be played, and an opponent, Bosnia, to be knocked down.
After the first leg (0-0), Friday in Zenica's inferno, it seems obvious that the games are not done.
Portugal dominated the game for more than an hour, of course, but it was unable to score that precious goal, which would have relieved it.
"It's a good result, but it carries a certain risk because we didn't score a goal on the outside."
But at home, in their bright Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced to pass, in front of an audience that should be there as hot, even if the game obviously promises to be "very tight", said an optimistic but lucid Bento.
“We expect a very close match, but we are quite confident that we can take over,” said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
“We continue to have a 50% chance of being at Euro 2012,” said Queiroz’s successor.
The draw reported Friday from Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
A draw can be enough for the Bosnians, who also need to score.
“It’s a good result, but it carries a certain risk because we didn’t score a goal on the outside,” Bento said.
“We’re going to play against a team that has a lot of technical qualities and has players with a lot of individual qualities,” he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will intend to put as much pressure on the Bosnians as possible in order not to “give them time to think.”
A good idea, as long as you are realistic this time.
